{"actual_usd":0.15873,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":197,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31155,"reply":"\"To the Father.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, buying half a beat because I want to answer cleanly and not cute.* \"Not in the cheap sense of 'God talking to himself'—Christians mean one God, yes, but not one Person. Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are distinct Persons.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"So in Gethsemane, the Son is really praying to the Father. That's not theater. It's a real relation inside the life of God—and because Jesus also took on a real human nature, it's also the human obedience of the Son, in flesh, under sorrow, submitting to the Father's will.\"\n\n\"If somebody says the Trinity is easy, they're bluffing. But no—Gethsemane isn't fake prayer. It's one of the places Christians think you can actually see both truths at once: Jesus is truly God, and Jesus is not the Father.\"","rolling_24h_usd":43.37942000000004,"run_id":"e6dccd96-998f-4d07-b22a-77bae3cc21c7"}
